Introduction

My first dataset, “SAT” discusses SAT scores and educational expenditures across states distribution among states.It is a data frame with 50 observations (1 per state) for the following variables: state, expend, ratio, salary, frac, verbal, math, and sat. My second dataset, “US arrests” has the statistics in arrests per 100,000 residents of the 50 states for assault, murder, and rape. It contains 50 observations for the four variables: murder, assault, urbanpop, and rape. I am interested in exploring the relationship between the variable “expend” from the SAT dataset, which is the expenditure per pupil in average daily attendance in public elementary and secondary schools, in thousands of US dollars and the variable “Murder”, which is numeric murder arrests per 100,000, in the US arrests dataset. I am mostly interested in if there is a relationship between the educational expenditures and murder arrests in the 1990s.I would expect higher educational expenditures to result in lower murder arrests, and vice versa.

I did an inner join of the two datasets in order to drop any row in either dataset without a match; however, because they are joined by the state variable, there will be no drops because there are 50 states in both. Data1 initially contained 50 rows and 9 columns, and therefore 450 observations, while data2 initially contained 50 rows and 5 columns, and therefore 250 observations. The resulting dataset has 50 rows and 13 columns, making a total of 650 observations. Both datasets contained the same number of states (50) before joining, and the combined dataset has 50 states. Therefore, there were no unique states present in one dataset over the other prior to joining. No observations in each dataset were dropped after doing the join. #### Wrangling

The three states with average total SAT scores less than 1000 and the highest murder rates are: Georgia, Florida, and South Carolina, and the three states with average total SAT scores less than 1000 and the lowest expenditure per pupil in average daily attendance are: Idaho, Arizona, and South Carolina. I would expect states with lower SAT scores to be the schools with the lowest educational expenditures because there is lack of funding towards their students suggesting lack of emphasis on allocating monetary resources to education. Therefore, I would assume that these states would have higher murder rates, solely based on statewide trends regarding education priorities. Because South Carolina has average sat scores of less than 1000, the third highest murder rates, and the third lowest expenditures per pupil, there can be some sort of loose indication of a negative relationship between expenditures and murder arrests. This could suggest that states that spend more on educating their citizens may be prone to higher SAT scores and less murders, and vice versa. I used mutate to create the variable “totalcrimes” which adds the variables “Murder”, “Assault”, “Rape” in order to create a variable that has the combined numeric murder, assault and rape arrests per 100,000 in order to better visualize crime rates holistically rather than individually. After computing the mean number of murders, assaults and rapes among all the states, alongside the mean number of total arrests, it is evident that assaults make up the vast majority of arrests, with murder and rape making up little number of arrests among all of the states. This makes sense as assault is a much broader category than murder than rape making its occurrence much larger.

Visualizing

ggplot(statesjoined, aes(expend, Murder)) + geom_point(aes(color = state)) + 
    ggtitle("Murder vs Expenditures") + xlab("Expenditure per pupil in average daily attendance ($1000s)") + 
    ylab("Numeric\tMurder arrests (per 100,000)") + geom_smooth(method = "lm")

There is a slight negative relationship between numeric murder arrests (per 100,000) and expenditure per pupil in average daily attendance. While I had anticipated a stronger correlation, it is sufficient to expect that state’s that spend more on students in average daily attendance could possibly lead to better education and therefore less murder arrests. However, there is a gap between the age of the students in school and those being arrested for murder, so expenditures could have shifted over the years. The purpose of the chart is to see the general trends per states to see if states that prioritize finances on educating their citizens more have less murder arrests.

ggplot(data = statesjoined, aes(x = state, y = totalcrimes, fill = state)) + 
    geom_bar(stat = "identity") + geom_point() + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, 
    hjust = 1)) + xlab("State") + ylab("Numeric\tmurder, assault and rape arrests per 100,000") + 
    ggtitle("Arrests by State") + theme(legend.position = "none")

*This bar plot showcases the total combined numeric murder, assault, and rape arrests per 100,000 for each state. Florida has the highest value of arrests,at 382.3 per 100,000 while North Dakota has the least at 53.1 per 100,000.Michigan has the lowest “expend”, or expenditure per pupil in average daily attendance in public elementary and secondary schools, 1994-95 (in thousands of US dollars),and South Dakota has the lowest “salary”, or estimated average annual salary of teachers in public elementary and secondary schools (in thousands of US dollars), while New Jersey has the highest “expend” and Connecticut has the highest “salary”; it is important to note though that Connecticut has the fourth highest expend. Therefore, this suggests there may be some relationship between salary of teachers and pupil expenditures. However, this data does not suffice to support any significant noticeable trends. The final plot of boxplots of sat scores by state showcases that South Carolina has the lowest value for “sat”, or average total SAT score, at 844 and North Dakota has the highest at 1107. As seen in previous analyses, North Dakota has the lowest value of arrests; this along with its highest SAT score average may indicate that the state overall prioritizes education of students more which may lead to a lower overall number of arrests.

Overall, there was no significant indication that there is a large negative correlation between expenditures per pupil and murder arrests, or arrests in general. Further and more in depth study would have to occur. Furthermore, timelines of the data may contribute in the sense that while both data was collected was collected in the same time frame, those of the age of being arrested may have been significantly older than that of school-going age, and may have not attended school in that specific state. This study was just intended to see state trends overall regarding educational expenditures/prioritization versus crime arrests, as it would be expected that higher levels of education would result in less crime. * )
